<a name="learned"></a>
## 📚 What I Learned

This internship was my first hands-on experience applying AI and Python to build real, working software from scratch. Here's what I actually understood and built:

### Natural Language Processing (Task 2)
- How raw text is cleaned and normalized before an AI model can use it
- What **tokenization** means — splitting sentences into individual words
- What **stopwords** are and why they're removed (words like "the", "is", "a" add noise)
- What **stemming** is — reducing words to their root form so "running" and "run" match
- How **TF-IDF** converts words into numbers based on importance
- How **Cosine Similarity** measures how "close" two pieces of text are in meaning
- Why a chatbot needs a **confidence threshold** — so it doesn't give wrong answers with fake confidence

### Computer Vision & Deep Learning (Task 4)
- What a **pre-trained model** is — YOLOv8 was trained by Ultralytics on millions of images so I didn't have to train it myself
- What **inference** means — running a trained model on new data (my webcam feed)
- What **bounding boxes** are — the rectangles drawn around detected objects
- What **object tracking** is vs **object detection** — detection finds objects in one frame, tracking follows them across many frames with a consistent ID
- How **MediaPipe** works — lightweight neural networks running frame-by-frame to detect body landmarks
- What **landmarks** are — specific key points on a body (wrist, knee, etc.) represented as (x, y) coordinates
- How **threading** works — running the heavy detection code in a background thread so the UI window stays responsive
- Why **OpenCV** is essential — it is the backbone of all image/video operations in Python

### General Python Skills
- Building complete **desktop applications** with Tkinter
- Organizing code into **classes** (OOP — Object-Oriented Programming)
- Using **try/except** for safe error handling so the app doesn't crash unexpectedly
- Managing **library version compatibility** (MediaPipe breaking change taught me this)
- Writing **clean, documented code** with comments explaining every section

